This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: Teaching us! We are here to learn and since the last evaluation (which I believe some of my other pod mates remarked on as well), nothing has changed. It's unfortunate that regardless of what is said in this evaluation, changes don't happen within this pod. We are on our last stretch of schooling and Dr. Huska has more than enough knowledge to share with us to make us feel like we've learned something this rotation. Our rounds time is wasted by her "ranting" about matters irrelevant to chiropractic and our learning. Her first 20 minutes of rounds where she can "check her emails", is unnecessary and a waste of our time. That is 20 minutes that we could be learning something, or even self directed learning within our pod. It is incredibly frustrating to hear that CMT has approved these 20 minutes of every rounds day for her to waste our time. That's 60 minutes each week we automatically lose. Dr. Huska has amazing potential to be a great teacher. She has shown us that in small pieces, and she is a wonderful support system for us. I just wish, and I'm sure I can speak for my pod mates, that we could learn something in the time that we are given.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: The only thing that Dr. Barrigar can improve on is he sometimes gets off topic when explaining things. When he does get off topic he will eventually relate it to the topic of discussion. However, this makes it hard to get through all the topics of discussion scheduling during rounds.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: Tends to give us a diagnosis before we have time to discuss possible diagnosis.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: Not a lot. Maybe have some business rounds every now and then but I know he is working on getting us to do an outreach with him to recruit patients. The man with the plan, Dr. Bonar is an amazing clinician and his future at CMCC is very bright.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: Can be stressed, uptight and very particular. Wants things worded his way, or performed his way. I also find he can harp on some interns more and praise others more. There is some apparent preferential inconsistency there.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: Possibly marks too easily. Not much done in rounds. Very conservative when deciding whether or not to adjust.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: N/a

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: Feedback was intense and pointed at times and may impede supplementary dialogue between the clinician and intern. However, this style of feedback may work very well for communicating to other interns.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: I value the information and learning that happens during our rounds time. I feel that there is downtime during rounds that could be used for further discussion, learning opportunities, etc.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: RoDr. Chiu is super smart and full of great clinical knowledge, I would love to see him teach and demo more often.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: efficiency, also hope we can do more technique rounds

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: I would like some more technique time during rounds.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: Demonstrating manual therapies.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: Generally speaking, nothing major here. Very happy with this rotation. My only regret is not doing it sooner. Perhaps Howitt could reflect on being more approachable and non-threatening to student observers. Some students may be naive to aspects of the clinical process at St. John's, or they may feel nervous/uncomfortable in a new setting and it would be beneficial to empower these students to learn and share their perspectives, rather than belittle them. I completely understand that some may deserve it (I get it), but sometimes the smarties/capable students get nervous and flustered, with the result being their potential may be inhibited by the environment created at St. John's.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: Could improve on patience, and letting the intern critically think or re-assess before jumping in/belittling the student. This will likely come with experience. Additionally, would prove beneficial to do some reading on pain science. Clinician displayed limited knowledge, or application of knowledge of pain and patient perception of pain. This was clearly exhibited with discussion of ROF and POM. Pretty disappointing to see patients' POM delivered solely on explicit guidelines without the necessary additional context that involves the principle of pain science.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: I believe that the way someone speaks to another person, especially when speaking to someone that is "inferior" to you, says a lot about who you are. When speaking to interns, she makes it quite clear that she is above us, that she is much more intelligent and that we are all incompetent. She could improve on how she speaks to others in general. It is not hard to pick up on her negative body language (eye rolling, sighing, glare etc) which is not conducive to a positive learning environment and makes everyone not want to approach her for help, which is really the worst thing, especially when dealing with patients. It would be beneficial for her to remember that we are still learning, and that she was in our shoes once. I know that she is a competent and intelligent resident and I am sure that she is up to date with the research...which are all fine qualities to have in a clinician. What is more valuable to me, is how I am spoken to, how I am taught and if I feel I am in a comfortable learning environment; which she never creates. I do not appreciate being spoken to the way I was spoken to and I felt there was a lack of respect. I do not think it is a positive thing to have a clinician that everyone dreads encountering, especially when there is something bigger going on: the care of the patients. Yes, she has more experience than us and two more years of education, but when you break it down, we are all equals and she is not that far ahead of us. She was just recently an intern too, which I think she needs to remember and take into consideration when dealing with current interns, especially when she is placed in a respected position such as a clinician. I would have more respect for her if she treated others with respect, consideration, kindness and not in a condescending manner. I apologize for the long paragraph, however this is something that I think will benefit future interns; if she simply treated people better.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: It is good to receive constructive criticism however it is also good to know what we are doing well; she seldom tells us when we are doing something well. She also tends to take over with the patient during comps. It would be beneficial to allow us to finish with the patient and then outside of the room, she can tell us what we missed-would benefit learning.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: The clinician could create a more positive learning environment and provide some positive feedback.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: Being more approachable/open-minded. Also to not second guess our decisions in front of the patients -- makes the intern and patient awkward.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: At times the environment in the clinic becomes a bit challenging. I wouldn't say that it deters me from the clinic, I would not have changed my choice either way. The challenges when framed in a positive mind frame actually help to increase my knowledge. There is a discrepency across ways in which clinicians diagnose and this makes this a little difficult as they do not understand each others methods at times. A emphasis can be make on making the environment in the clinic a bit more positive.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: Would love to do more practical rounds. Learning new adjustment or treatment techniques.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: Continue to challenge us and make us better by asking questions in the LO presentations or just continue to pull from his past experiences to drive a point home about a new learning topic.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: Was preoccupied with recruiting patients to a study he will author through CMCC. Some patients did not feel comfortable with an MRI study after being treated (with varying results) through chiropractic, while some patients did not think their pain was too bad to warrant participation in a study.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: More practical rounds to be done. The past month we learned a lot of the physiology and biomechanical knowledge of muscles, joints, and healing. However, I personally would like to see more of the practical rounds that were done at the beginning of the rotation. Would also like to see more practical rounds on how to communicate with patients as a whole. It is something we need to work on as students, and I feel that it should have more emphasis. Communicating with the pod that if they are eating foods with strong aromas (i.e. eggs) that they should be eating it in the bistro or caf.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: I think I need to be challenged a little more in why I'm asking the questions I'm asking & doing the tests I'm doing, as I still feel I am not efficient in my history/physical exam. A little more feedback (positive & negative) would also be helpful so I can continue to learn and improve.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: Constructive criticism rather than condescending criticism

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: providing more constructive feedback so we can continue to develop into better interns

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: Based on situations I have witnessed the attending clinician can improve on being more approachable and the way in which she provides feedback. I have not witnessed but through pod mates have heard with providing feedback she rolls her eyes or will make comments that be little you as an intern. Hearing this and witnessing it makes me hesitate to approach her as a clinician. In addition one intern had a complex case in which the attending clinician was requiring the intern to perform extra work when the clinician stepped into the room stating that the shift ends in five minutes you need to hurry up as I have to leave. I feel as though this was inappropriate as we as interns are not paid to be an intern in general and stay past our working hours to get the job done as we are passionate and want to learn and not rush while the clinician is rushing the intern to finish the work for the day as the shift is almost done. Dr. Tavares has ingrained in us that we don't leave the clinic until all the patient work is done. I think this made the intern feel uneasy and rushed as she had some many questions for the clinician. This adds stress to the interns and doesn't create an environment to learn and grow.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: She is a liability to patients. She advised a patient who had red flags to go to the emergency room if his symptoms worsened, however she made the huge mistake of not informing the patient of her suspicions regarding his health. When I questioned her as to why she did not inform the patient of her suspicions, she said she didn't want to scare him. This is an egregious mistake on her part, she did a diservice to the patient and showed lack of competence. Instead she went over sleep hygiene when clearly he was not well and to top things off she took him to the book store (after me telling her and she witnessing his swollen ankles, laboured breathing etc) to look for a pillow. When I approached her again asking her if I could call the patient to correct her mistake and tell him to go to the hospital, she discussed it with me briefly and then said she wanted to talk about it further before I call, so she told me to wait while she worked on checking SOAP notes. After 45 mins, I broached the subject again and literally asked to finish talking about the issue because it involves the patient's safety, she barked at me and said she see's me sitting there and to wait my turn. She was not doing anything that urgent, she just wanted to draw a line in the sand. Many other interns witnessed this and were astonished (as we usually are at her poor behaviour) and told me to tell CMT about it. In this case and other cases she refuses to deal with patients, instead choosing to avoid them at all costs. Dr. Huska has an inability to communicate effectively with patients and her interns. Patients have told me that they are on the verge of leaving her pod to go to a different clinician but they are scared of her. That is not good practice management. Patients should not fear their chiropractor. Dr. Huska creates a very negative learning environment which is oppressive and unprofessional to say the least. The sad part is that she is her only obstacle and lacks the ability to self reflect on her behaviour and make the changes necessary. She is constantly yelling at us for things we haven't done "wrong", mistakes we have not made etc. If we say anything, she tells us (she has said and done this to all of the interns, not just myself) we are sensitive, or argumentative. She mistakes our facial expressions for sensitivity when in fact it is total astonishment and disdain at her lack of professionalism, as well as the inappropriateness of her behaviour and comments. She is disrespectful to others and I think that is why she gets a feeling that we do not respect her; when in fact we are reacting to being so poorly treated by her. Dr. Huska wastes an enormous amount of time rambling and ranting about her personal problems and opinions that have no clinical relevance what so ever. As adults, we should have the choice to be subject to her angry diatribes and yet we are not allowed to speak, or leave the room during rounds - so basically we are made to sit there and take all of this negativity. She then has us do a meditation session on her iphone, which in and of it self becomes something for her to argue with us about. She argues constantly with us over every small detail just for the sake of creating negativity and conflict. She dumps all of the work of doing competency's on the resource clinicians. The resource has to allocate time to all three pods, but she literally tells us to go and take advantage of them, to have all cases prepared for them to go over. How can a resource go over 7 of my case narratives in one day? She spends so much time rambling and ranting during rounds that we get nothing done but then she wants the resources to do the work.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: He mentions that it is required of us to involve him in on patient developments, but then seems dismissive when questions are asked about findings I am unsure of.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: nothing that's worth sharing on this type of evaluation assessment, with all due respect.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: Creating a more team based environment to work in, with group cohesion etc. Perhaps more activities in education time that foster a collaborative atmosphere.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: Providing a proportional amount of both positive and negative feedback. Generally, feedback about our pod in particular was negative. I do not think it is reasonable that the clinician express his displeasure with the work ethic and attitudes of the pod REGARDLESS of what he/she believes to be true. Providing us with such feedback does not promote a healthy learning environment and increases tension between the interns and clinician. I feel most of this animosity was generated over the decision to withdraw the application process for external clinics. Dr. Chung was quite clear that he was not provided with the "usual" caliber of interns.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: n/a

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: more hands on technique

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: Demonstrating more assessment and treatment techniques that you utilize. Get paperwork back in a timely fashion.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: Place an emphasis on teaching and providing useful clinical experiences. Giving more appropriate feedback regarding patient care. The majority of the pod wants to learn during rounds yet all we do is read case reports and learning objectives. The clinician should provide a better learning environment in general.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: Addressing the questions in a more direct manor. Working on not becoming distracted in response to questioning. Better usage of time, the first one hour of rounds is spent sitting around and waiting, and the second hour is spent conversing. An alternative to this would be to do rounds for the first hour and finish early.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: Giving positive feedback more often

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: Being approachable.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: Having more of a discussion regarding differential diagnoses for new patients and re evals.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: being more open to interns using treatment options that he may not use or like.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: I would like to learn a little bit more in terms of manual skills and physical exam skills, because I feel that Dr. Harris has a lot of knowledge in these areas - particularly on things we didn't learn while at CMCC.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: would like to have an adjusting rounds where we are taught new adjustments, some communication regarding expectations and how he wants things to be done at the very start of the rotation (although there were no major issues if something was done differently, just timing/efficiency might have been effected in some regards)

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: Take initiative in teaching such as technique rounds or more current topics in chiropractic/manual therapy practise. It feels like we (interns) are teaching each other more than the clinician is.

Question: This attending clinician could improve in:
Comments: Encouraging us to look into new treatment methods we may not think of or be exposed to at CMCC.

This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Incredibly knowledgable

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: When she does decide to teach, she is good at teaching us safe, effective ways to treat patients. Her techniques are great but unfortunately only get to learn about them in small 20 minute segments once every few weeks. She gives great feedback while doing the competencies.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Dr. Barrigar has been a great teacher and mentor. He has introduced to us concepts and ideas for patient management that I never even considered before this rotation. He is a very knowledge and has been very effective at translating his knowledge to concepts that makes it easy to understand. Ever day in clinic I have learnt something from Dr. Barrigar. I really am enjoying this rotation and look forward to discussion with my clinician in this rotation

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Dr. Engel is a great teacher and has a lot of experience in this profession. He is also very good at connecting and communicating with patients

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Outstanding clinician. Excellent teacher, he always explains why he does things and gives excellent feedback. He ensure you are caught up on all your paperwork. Dr. Bonar is always aware of what is going on with the pod at all times. Great diagnostician. Does a very good job coming up with round topics and ensuring we are learning something new every day. Approachable and friendly. I encountered an uncomfortable situation and he dealt with it very professionally. The one thing we are trying to do here in our internship is learn how to be a proficient, patient-centered chiropractor. Dr. Bonar excels at determining what our weaknesses are and addressing them to ensure we blow the roof off when we graduate. I would pick him first overall if I had to select clinicians again.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Teaching. Loves to teach! Does not really matter what he is teaching, you can tell he has a passion for educating students. Is usually open-minded about different aspects of health care and is okay with having outside-the-box discussions which often prove fruitful and allows for self-reflection which is a higher level of thinking. His hands-on rounds are usually excellent as well.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Incredible knowledge. Gives great positive feedback. Amazing at performing Hx, Phx and coming up with DDXs + POMs

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Dr. Moser is particularly skilled at providing critical and constructive feedback in a way that is conducive to learning. He highlights future learning opportunities well and encourages interns to excel.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Teaching interns during rounds time. I value Dr. Tuff's clinical pearls and lessons.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Dr. Oleson is particularly skilled at determining learning gaps and outlining them to students. Her feedback was very valuable.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: I truly value Dr. Kissel's input and feedback. I feel that she is approachable with any concerns and questions I have. She creates a very inclusive learning environment that allows each intern to develop their own unique skills.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Being available and approachable. Is never rude or condescending when asking a question.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: very sympathetic, helps intern view things at a different angle

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: making a non threatening learning environment. Has a good balance of giving us autonomy with our patients but still willing to come into the treatment room when necessary

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Gives excellent constructive feedback; Creates an open learning environment;

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Helping to develop ddx list for complaints and encouraging broader thinking. Helpful in improving technique skills.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: He is very good at helping you refine your assessment skills and tying it back to anatomy. Every time he comes by he always teaches me something new or helps with an adjustment.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: He is very good at helping you think of the injury itself and what is occurring locally and distally from the injury site. It helps you understand the injury, and express your clinical findings in relation to it. He helped me simplify my doctors letter.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: She has helped me improve my technique skills and refine my clinical skills every time she comes by.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Giving me the space and autonomy for me to develop my own clinical reasoning.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Guiding a thought process rather than giving answers.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: communicating clinical expertise

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Excellent discussion. Poses terrific questions to the group to faciliate learning and critical thinking. This extra effort and positive attitude is greatly appreciated and the learning environment has been great.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Sharing the current evidence on the topic of interest. Clinician is clearly proficient with the current guidelines.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: It is difficult to think of something positive to say. She gave some good feedback about comps but the way she delivered the feedback was undesirable and quite frankly, condescending. If one can look past the tone she uses and the eye rolling she delivers when giving feedback, she has some constructive feedback to give. She is good at having knowledge about the literature.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: She is a wonderful teacher and is always prepared with subjects and presentations to present to us. I have learned a lot from her and every day she has something to teach. She is wonderful at multi-tasking and when she speaks to you, she speaks to you on your level. She gives you her 100% attention when she needs to and can recognize what needs to be prioritized. She is wonderful with patients as well.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: The clinician is good at taking the time to teach and go over student's palpation skills. The clinician checks whether the student's skills are coming along.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Adjustments and giving advice/tips to try to improve adjustment skills

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: I have improved significantly upon coming into this rotation. Palpation skills as well as adjusting skills have been the greatest asset provided by Dr. Steiman

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Making us efficient with our treatments. Providing us with feedback about proper positioning so we don't get injured in practice.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Creating a learning environment that challenged us but instilled confidence in our decision making. Does not give us the answer but cues us along to finding it ourselves.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Had a mid rotation talk about our goals and what we wanted to change in regards to rounds to better optimize our time. Was very open to altering our current format to better utilize our time to be more productive. Adding in his two cents after LO presentations has helped solidify some good take home points from the presentations and makes them more applicable to our day to day practice.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Explaining nerve common issues, how to resolve them, and the use of toggle boards for extremity adjustments.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Emphasizing the use of clinical outcome measures such as NDI and the Oswestry Pain Scale

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Providing feedback for things that we struggle with. His up to date knowledge on evidence and how it applies to clinical practice. Very informative educational rounds.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Presenting current topics in an informative and interesting manner

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Relaying clinical reasoning for the treatment plan length and the delivery of Adverse events (for ROF). Dr. Moser did this in a way that promoted learning, and I was comfortable enough to ask all the questions I had in mind. He was approachable, and I enjoyed learning from him.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: I feel like my ability to generate a differential list beyond mechanical is improving due to Dr. Tavares' prompting. I appreciated the rounds sessions that focused on the different conditions, pathopnuemonic signs, and current evidence based treatment.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: I appreciate that Dr. Lishchyna gives us our autonomy in practice, but is always around and checking up on us when we need it. It makes the experience more realistic, as opposed to other clinicians who may be more strict and wanting to control the situation.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Creating a very good learning environment. Very approachable.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Very useful rounds topics!

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Providing good feedback about comps.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: The clinician treats her pod as her own children and makes sure that we are aware of upcoming dates etc as well as schedules learning sessions for our rounds that facilitate learning above what we have asked for (ie. auscultation rounds). She is passionate about teaching and it really shows in the way she teaches us not only during rounds and clinic but also communicating with us and sharing new research and topics to search.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: I have only experienced working with this clinician on one occasion. The attending clinician is very knowledgeable

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: I learn something every single day I'm in clinic! It seems like Dr. Lee can't even help but teach. You don't have to try to pull information out of him because he will use every opportunity that presents itself to teach. With that being said, he will also gladly answer questions that you have. I think there is a very appropriate balance between him expecting us to come up with information on our own and him providing information. I also really appreciated the hands-on learning. We had a lot of active rounds, which gave us the opportunity to practice our skills. I appreciated that Dr. Lee would demonstrate something and then expect us to practice it immediately afterwards. I think this is important because if the pod is not eager to practice and learn and the clinician does not demonstrate that they expect the pod to practice, the students who are eager to practice do not get this opportunity. That is the situation I found myself in during the first rotation and it has been so much more beneficial having a clinician who expects us to practice our hands-on skills.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Nothing. She is a horrible clinician.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Rounds discussions, attention to clinical development

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: rehab rounds and teaching us different ways of testing various muscle groups or ortho tests

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: ...at educating and fulfilling the expectations (and beyond) of the duties at hand. His feedback for me clearly outlines what I am doing wrong and what I could improve on. He's excellent at articulating what he wants to say. The more I got to know Dr. Chung, the more I started to understand his point of views and his perspective on things. He doesn't just give surface-level thought-process. He delves into the more abstract thinking and weighs both sides of the argument.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Taking the individual concerns of interns into account and providing personalized feedback on areas of proficiency and room for improvement. Teaching about topics not always covered in the curriculum including chronic pain and shoe fitting etc.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Provoking critical thinking in determining a diagnosis and treatment plan. Effective communication with patients and was actively involved in their care. Promoted us to research topics related to our patient cases.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: challenging us on treatment plans and informing us about vibration therapy

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: teaching us when to use diagnostic U/S and how to interpret images

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Promoting questions from open discussion concerning chiropractic as a whole and patient centered.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Giving me autonomy and allowed me to direct self learning.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Keeping a positive atmosphere.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Answering and responding to questions while asked.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Patient interaction, making all the patients feel as though as they are important and valued.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Providing us with recent high quality articles to read, to promote our learning. Providing us with strategies to help communicate effectively with our patients.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: sharing/teaching effective protocols for treating common conditions. has made more time for teaching, which is great. he is good at keeping patient files organized and up to date.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Showing us the importance of a detailed examination and history when deciding how to approach a clinical scenario. Also the importance of staying up to date with current literature and how to apply it to clinical practice.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: encouraging learning and promoting teaching during clinic hours

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Teaching.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: encouraging interns to self-evaluate themselves, giving autonomy, increasing teaching time (ie. implementing rounds) in comparison to period 4

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: demonstrating physical exam techniques for a more accurate diagnosis

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: #NAME?

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: #NAME?

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Very approachable and friendly. Great discussions.

Question: This attending Clinician was especially good at:
Comments: Confirming and supporting what we choose to do for our plan of managements. Promoted independency.
